'''Smith, Elder & Co.''' was a firm of British publishers who were most noted for the works they published in the 19th century.

The firm was founded by [[George Smith (publisher)|George Smith]] (1789&ndash;1846) and [[Alexander Elder (publisher)|Alexander Elder]] (1790&ndash;1876) and successfully continued by [[George Murray Smith]] (1824&ndash;1901).

They are notable for producing the first edition of the ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]'' (DNB). 

The firm achieved its first major success with the publication of [[Charlotte Bront<U+00EB>]]'s ''[[Jane Eyre]]'' in 1847, under the pseudonym of "Currer Bell." Other major authors published by the firm' included [[Robert Browning]], [[George Eliot]], [[Elizabeth Gaskell]], [[Thomas Hardy]], [[Richard Jefferies]], [[George MacDonald]], [[Charles Reade]], [[John Ruskin]], [[Algernon Charles Swinburne]], [[Alfred Tennyson]] and [[George Gissing]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36138 |title=George Murray Smith (1824<U+2013>1901) |publisher=oxforddnb.com |accessed=5 October 2010}}</ref>

In addition, beginning in 1841, they published ''The London and Edinburgh Magazine''.

==Books published by Smith, Elder & Co.==
* ''[[Morocco in Diplomacy (book)|Morocco in Diplomacy]]'' by [[Edmund Dene Morel]], 1912
* ''[[Jane Austen|Jane Austen: Her Life and Letters, A Family Record]]'' by [[William and Richard Arthur Austen-Leigh]], 1913

